# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: efficient-energy-use
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:efficient-energy-use/2019-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2019.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2019-in-climate-change] National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA).
[src:efficient-energy-use/2020-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2020.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2021-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2021.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2021-in-climate-change] among climate experts (2010–2015) reflect that the level of scientific consensus correlates with expertise in climate science.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2021-in-climate-change] and a 2021 study concluded that consensus exceeded 99%.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2021-in-climate-change] Another 2021 study found that 98.7% of climate experts indicated that the Earth is getting warmer mostly because of human activity.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2022.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] A 2022 study found that the public substantially underestimates the degree of scientific consensus that humans are causing climate change.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] found scientific consensus to range from 98.7–100%.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] Research found that 80–90% of Americans underestimate the prevalence of support for major climate change mitigation policies and climate concern.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] While 66–80% Americans support these policies, Americans estimate the prevalence to be 37–43%.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2022-in-climate-change] National political divides on the seriousness of climate change consistently correlate with political ideology, with right-wing opinion being more negative.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2023.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The **2023 United Nations Climate Change Conference** or **Conference of the Parties of the UNFCCC**, more commonly known as **COP28**, was the 28th United Nations Climate Change conference, held from 30 November to 13 December at Expo City Dubai.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The COP conference has been held annually (except for the year 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic) since the first UN climate agreement in 1992.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The event is intended for governments to agree on policies to limit global temperature rises and adapt to impacts associated with climate change.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference was originally scheduled to end on 12 December, but had to be extended following Saudi objections on the final agreement.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 13 December, the conference president, Sultan Al Jaber announced that a final compromise agreement between the countries involved had been reached.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The deal commits all signatory countries to move away from carbon energy sources "in a just, orderly and equitable manner" to mitigate the worst effects of climate change, and reach net zero by the year 2050.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China and India did not sign the pledge to triple their output of renewable energy and committed to coal power instead.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The conference was widely criticised for its controversial president Sultan Al Jaber, as well as its host country, the United Arab Emirates, which is known for its opaque environmental record and role as a major producer of fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Al Jaber is the CEO of the Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (ADNOC), leading to concerns over conflict of interest.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Al Jaber stated before the beginning of the conference that there was "no science" behind fossil fuel phase-out in achieving 1.5 °C; and leaked documents appeared to show the UAE planned to use the conference to strike new fossil fuel deals with other nations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Al Jaber claimed that his comments on the phase-out of fossil fuels were "misinterpreted" and denied the latter allegation, asserting that the UAE does not need the COP presidency to establish business deals.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United Nations Climate Change Conference is an annual conference of all countries that have signed the 1994 United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It is held annually, with the host countries rotating among its current members.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In early 2021, the United Arab Emirates offered to host the 2023 event.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Dubai was chosen as the host city in November of the same year.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was the third time it was hosted by a member of OPEC after Indonesia in 2007 and the then member Qatar in 2012.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The United Arab Emirates is one of the most climate-vulnerable countries in the world, due to its very hot and humid climate.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Its average air temperature has risen by 1.27 °C (2.29 °F) between 1990 and 2022.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Red Sea and Persian Gulf have exceeded safe wet-bulb temperature thresholds several times.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Other impacts felt in the region are more frequent dust storms, sea level rise and drought.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE has committed to reducing carbon emissions to net zero by 2050; the first Middle Eastern government to make such a pledge.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was also the first country in the region to sign the Paris Agreement on 21 September 2016.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The country has invested $50 billion into clean energy internationally and promised an additional $50 billion by 2030.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The choice of the UAE as host country was criticized by many climate scientists and human rights advocates around the globe, as the country is both a leading oil producer and an authoritarian state without freedom of speech.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Emirati organisers warned speakers not to criticise Islam or the Emirati government, corporations or individuals.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Human Rights Watch urged governments to use the opportunity to push the UAE to ease the "grip on civic space and uphold rights" and end the persecution of human rights activists like Ahmed Mansoor.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 1 August 2023, the UAE allowed environmental activists to "assemble peacefully" at the summit and vowed to provide them a space to "make their voices heard", despite laws that prohibit unauthorised protests.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE's appointment of Sultan Al Jaber president of COP28 caused further controversy, as he is also the CEO of the Abu Dhabi National Oil Company (ADNOC).
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In February 2023, one month after Al Jaber's selection, the company announced plans to expand drilling for fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] More than 100 members of the European Parliament, U.S. senators and U.S. representatives signed a joint open letter calling on the UAE to withdraw Al Jaber's appointment.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] U.S. climate envoy John Kerry acknowledged Al Jaber's selection as COP president was "risky", but nonetheless supported it, arguing it was important to have fossil fuel producers at the table.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In June 2023, a report by *The Guardian* revealed that ADNOC shared an email server with COP28 and was able to read emails to and from the climate summit office.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The COP28 office switch to a different server following *The Guardian*'s inquiry.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the months leading up to the summit, joint preparations were held by the United States of America, China and the European Union.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] (John Kerry), China (Xie Zhenhua) and the EU (Frans Timmermans) met regularly to discuss priorities and planning.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 15 November, the U.S. and China announced an agreement to triple global renewable energy use by 2030.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The agreement included a commitment to addressing greenhouse gases, but was criticised for not including a commitment from China to phase out coal-fired power plants.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Insiders cautiously expressed hope for a climate agreement between China and the United States ahead of the conference, similar to the agreement of 2014 that paved the way for the Paris Agreement.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China published a plan to reduce methane emissions ahead of the conference, but there was expected contention on coal use in China.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China characterises coal as essential for its energy security, although others say energy security could be improved through upgrades to the energy grid and domestic energy market.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] At the end of November 2023, a pre-COP meeting of ministers was held.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] One hundred delegations and 70 ministers attended, more than any prior pre-COP meeting.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The general director of the COP, Majid al-Suwaidi, insisted the conference would fulfill the commitment to create a loss and damage fund, as was agreed at the 2022 United Nations Climate Change Conference.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE had initially invited the president of Syria, Bashar al-Assad, to COP28, resulting in widespread condemnation.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Assad ultimately did not come, sending his prime minister Hussein Arnous instead.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In September 2023, in advance of the opening of COP28, the United Nations published the first two-year assessment of global progress in slowing down climate change, called the "global stocktake".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] This type of overview was established during the 2021 COP26 in Glasgow and is scheduled to be repeated every five years.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The report concluded that a phase-out of fossil fuels is needed, something that the United Nations had previously avoided saying.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Governments expressed concern that similar to the Russian invasion of Ukraine, the 2023 Gaza war may adversely impact negotiations at COP28.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Before the conference, Pope Francis issued an apostolic exhortation called *Laudate Deum*, calling for brisk action against the climate crisis and condemning climate change denial.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The Pope planned to attend the conference, which would have marked the first papal visit to a United UN Climate Change conference, but had to pull out due to ill health.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] United States president Joe Biden did not attend, with the Gaza war and internal U.S. government spending difficulties being cited as possible causes.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to Professor Alon Tal, a renowned scholar of climate change issues, "There was no compelling reason to believe that the 2023 UN climate gathering would be any different than its predecessor and that significant progress would be made.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] As November approached, the prospects for the annual UN climate conference were hardly promising.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] COP28 was the largest-ever climate summit, with over 80,000 people accredited participants, up from 49,000 the previous year.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Twenty-three thousand five hundred of the participants were from government teams, including more than 150 heads of state and government.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A further 27,000 were policy experts, academics and representatives of fossil fuel producers, although this group was not given access to official negotiations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An additional 400,000 people were granted access to the surrounding "green zone", a conference space for activists and businesses.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The number of attendees and the use of private jets by many of them was the subject of some criticism.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The meeting was estimated to have the largest carbon footprint of any climate summit to date.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Charles III, King of the United Kingdom and the Commonwealth realms, gave the opening speech at the summit.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] He expressed alarm at rising levels of pollution, saying that the world was "dreadfully far off track" its climate targets and warning that "we are carrying out a vast, frightening experiment of changing every ecological condition, all at once, at a pace that far outstrips nature's ability to cope".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On the first day of the summit on 30 November 2023, a "loss and damage" fund to compensate poor states for the effects of climate change was agreed upon.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The fund aims to distribute funds to poor states harmed by climate change and is to be administered by the World Bank.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The host country, the United Arab Emirates, and Germany each pledged $100 million to the fund.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Smaller pledges by the United Kingdom ($75 million), United States ($24.5 million) and Japan ($10 million) brought the total to $430 million on the first day.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 1 December 2023, activists protested outside the venue, calling for ecocide—mass environmental destruction—to be made a crime at the International Criminal Court.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The same day, the Brazilian environment and finance ministers presented the Tropical Forest Forever Facility, an international investment instrument to fund tropical forest conservation.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 3 December 2023, COP28 participants launched the Declaration to Triple Nuclear Energy capacity from 2020 to 2050.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The declaration was unveiled by U.S. climate envoy John Kerry, and signed by 25 countries.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The signing countries pledged to implement policies to extend their nuclear capacities, stating that nuclear power played a key role in cutting carbon emissions to net zero.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 3 December 2023, *The Guardian* revealed that COP28 President Sultan Al-Jaber had dismissed demands for a fossil fuel phase-out two weeks previously, denying its basis in science and claiming it would prevent economic development.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The following day, Al-Jaber held a press conference in which he walked back his comments, stating that he stated he "respects science" and thinks a phaseout of fossil fuel use is inevitable.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 11 December, the day before the summit was scheduled to end, an initial draft of the final agreement was released.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It was widely rejected by most Western countries because it avoided calling for a fossil fuel phaseout; The Alliance of Small Island States described the draft as a "death certificate" for small island nations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Several African countries countered that wealthy countries had an obligation to take the lead on phasing out fossil fuels before expecting poorer countries to do so.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] OPEC, a cartel of oil-producing countries, also urged participants to reject any mention of phasing out fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] After two days of intense negotiations, a compromise was reached under which the final text called for countries to "end their dependence" on fossil fuels "in a just, orderly and equitable manner", while stopping short of calling for a full phase-out.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The agreement also called for a tripling of global renewable energy capacity by 2030, the development of numerous "zero- and low-emission technologies", further efforts "towards the phase-down of unabated coal power" and a cut in methane emissions.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The term *unabated* is generally understood to mean the use of carbon capture and storage, however the agreement left the term undefined.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] China and India did not sign the pledge to triple their output of renewable energy, and committed to coal power instead.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Moreover, the choice to include carbon capture and storage in the list of "zero- and low-emission technologies" was questioned due to its relative expensiveness and lack of effectiveness in comparison to other methods.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Numerous sessions at COP28 were devoted to the impact of climate change on public health; it was the first COP to address the topic.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] "Lethal humidity," or 100% humidity at temperatures of 35 °C (95 °F), was a particular focus of discussion.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Air pollution increases respiratory conditions and increases the risk of cancer and heart disease.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In a letter addressed to Sultan Al Jaber, "organisations representing more than 46 million health professionals" said a complete phase-out of fossil fuels was the only decisive way to deliver health for all.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Previously, experts such as Edmond Fernandes had urged UNFCCC to make public health an essential part of all climate meetings and policies, calling human health integral to sustainable climate futures.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] COP28 is the first COP where food systems were discussed.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] During the event, the UAE Declaration on Sustainable Agriculture, Resilient Food Systems, and Climate Action was adopted by 159 countries.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Two-thirds of the estimated 250,000 meals served at the event were plant-based.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UN's Food and Agriculture Organization issued a roadmap report at the event outlining how to reduce agricultural emissions from methane.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Prior to the conference, the UAE hired public relations and lobbying agencies, including Akin Gump Strauss Hauer & Feld, Gulstan Advisory and FleishmanHillard, to improve its poor reputation on climate change.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Allegations surfaced regarding attempts to manipulate public perception, including that Al Jaber's team had edited Wikipedia to portray him more favorably.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] ADNOC and Masdar also paid Wikipedia editors to lobby for changes to their respective pages, although the users followed Wikipedia's conflict-of-interest rules.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Reports also emerged of the proliferation of fake social media accounts on Twitter and Medium, aimed at promoting COP28 and defending the UAE's presidency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] For instance, one talking point instructed officials to deflect from ADNOC's refusal to disclose its emissions by responding, "ADNOC is currently conducting necessary studies".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Campaigning journalist Amy Westervelt argued that a newly added requirement to for industry lobbyists to identify themselves at COP28 was inadequate to control their influence.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] During the previous decade, the UAE had spent more than $1 million on direct climate-focused advocacy and paid millions more to public relations firms and think tanks to polish its green credentials.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] No other host nation has invested as much time and money to shape its image ahead of the annual climate negotiations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE hired a US-based PR firm, First International Resources, to "counteract all negative press and media reports" around the Gulf state as a COP28 host.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The agreement followed the negative criticism of the UAE's decision to assign Sultan Al Jaber as the COP28 president.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 4 August 2023, the company registered under the United States Foreign Agents Registration Act to represent Masdar.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the filings, the PR firm was supposed to seek to "reinforce attitudes among decision-makers in Washington, D.C., and across Europe regarding the strategic value of the UAE in the global fight to address climate change".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE was to pay First International Resources a monthly retainer fee of $100,000.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Fossil Free Media founder and director Jamie Henn said such an amount is not paid to a PR firm "when you're confident about your public image".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] He said that much is spent "when you want to spin the public to believe the impossible", such as the claim that the UAE and Al Jaber had been "really committed to transitioning away from fossil fuels".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In August 2023, *The Guardian* revealed that the UAE failed to report its methane emissions to the UN for nearly a decade.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Meanwhile, Sultan Al Jaber's ADNOC set a much higher methane leak target than the level it claimed to have already reached.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Cutting methane emissions is believed to be a fast and low-cost method to slow the temperature rise because methane causes almost a quarter of global heating.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In November of the same year, the Centre for Research on Energy reported that the UAE regularly flared methane gas, breaking its own regulations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Minister of Foreign Affairs Abdullah bin Zayed Al Nahyan commissioned a survey of over 20,000 from 20 countries, which was used by the officials to discuss the public attitude towards the Arab nation.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The major concerns were all about human rights.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] One of the participants, Sconaid McGeachin said COPs have become a platform for activism, and reportedly said: "We need to preserve the reputation of the UAE ... and try to minimise those attacks as much as possible".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A spokesperson for COP28, called the leaked recording "unverified", but stated that COP28 would "engage all stakeholders".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The UAE has been adapting its conference facility, the prior site for Expo 2020, to host the COP28 climate conference.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] FairSquare, a UK-based human rights group, released a report based on testimonies and photographs, stating that the migrant workers were being exposed to dangerously hot weather and humidity to prepare for the climate summit.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to the rights group, in September 2023, a dozen migrant workers from Asia and Africa were working outdoors in temperatures hitting 42 °C (108 °F) despite a midday ban.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] COP28 denied the allegations and claimed that no evidence of the midday ban's breach was found.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A worksite supervisor said most of the work is done at night, but some has to be done whenever possible.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] A COP28 spokesperson said contractors were required to have worker heat safety plans and weather stations that monitor the thermal work limit, as well as taking into account heat and humidity metrics including wet and dry bulb temperature and wind speed.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Ahead of COP28, Amnesty International raised concerns that the UAE might continue to use digital surveillance to spy on human rights defenders and civil society members in the UAE, including the COP28 participants.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to Amnesty International's Disrupting Surveillance Team, the UAE had a record of using digital surveillance to "crush dissents and stifle freedom of expression".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Amnesty's view of the UAE's promise to offer a "platform for activists' voices" would be unachievable without respect for the human rights of privacy and the right of peaceful assembly.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Amnesty opposed the "unlawful electronic surveillance of conference participants [and of] Emirati nationals and residents".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] It said that the COP28 attendees should be allowed to download "privacy-respecting international communications applications" in the UAE that would ensure safe and encrypted means of communication.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 7 November 2023, an AFP investigation revealed in multiple leaked documents that McKinsey was using its position as the primary advisor to COP28 hosts, the United Arab Emirates, to push the interest of its oil and gas clients (ExxonMobil and Aramco).
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] McKinsey has been accused of putting its own interests ahead of the climate by sources involved in preparatory meetings for COP28.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The report stated that fossil fuel talks between ADNOC and 15 countries were planned, in addition to talks between Masdar and 20 countries including the United Kingdom, France, Germany and others ahead of the summit.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Al Jaber denied reports that the UAE wanted to seek oil deals at the summit, calling the allegations an attempt to undermine his work.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] An analysis found that at least 2,456 COP28 attendees were fossil fuel lobbyists, receiving more passes than the ten countries most vulnerable to climate change.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Analysis by Oxfam found that 34 billionaires—together worth roughly $495 billion—attended COP28 as delegates; a quarter of them had made their money in "highly polluting industries".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Sultan Al Jaber, the president of COP28, has drawn criticism for asserting there is no scientific basis for phasing out fossil fuels to limit global warming to 1.5 degrees Celsius, a claim revealed by *The Guardian* and the Centre for Climate Reporting.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Described as "incredibly concerning" and bordering on climate denial, his comments contradict the stance of UN Secretary-General António Guterres.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The remarks were made during a confrontational exchange with Mary Robinson, chair of the Elders group, at a live online event on 21 November.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] *The Times* noted widespread condemnation of Al Jaber's statements at COP28, where numerous countries, including the UK and EU members, advocated for the phased reduction of unabated fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In contrast, former U.S. vice president Al Gore emphasised the historical significance of a potential COP28 agreement to phase out fossil fuels, considering it one of the most crucial events in human history.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Simultaneously, BBC News reported a substantial increase in the United Arab Emirates' oil production, with ADNOC, the state oil firm, projected to drill 42% more by 2030.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Despite this, ADNOC claims it aims to enhance climate-friendliness, including venturing into renewable energy, amid the global call for fossil fuel reduction.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 11 December 2023, Licypriya Kangujam, a climate activist from India, walked onto the main stage of the conference, held up a sign, "End fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Save our planet and our future.", and gave a brief speech.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] She was given a round of applause by the audience and removed from the session by security personnel.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] According to Kangujam, she was banned from further participation in COP28.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Other activists criticised the UAE's heavy restrictions on protests, which Human Rights Watch called "shocking".
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Protests at the summit were largely confined to the "blue zone", an area under UN control where local laws do not apply.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In the blue zone, local activists used COP28 as a platform for human rights demonstrations that are rare and generally not permitted in the UAE.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] New Westminster Mayor Patrick Johnstone attended the COP28 climate summit, with expenses covered by the C40 Cities Climate Leadership Group, in which Dubai is the part of Sterling Committee.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] This raised concerns about potential violations of the state's code of conduct.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In February 2024, Councilors Daniel Fontaine and Paul Minhas filed a complaint against Johnstone, alleging that he violated state laws by accepting gifts to attend the COP28 summit.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] This led to an investigation by ethics commissioner Jennifer Devins.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] In her September 2024 report, Devins concluded that while Johnstone's attendance was relevant to his mayoral duties, accepting gifts like travel and accommodation was not aligned with his official responsibilities.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] The head of the International Monetary Fund, Kristalina Georgieva, expressed satisfaction from the beginning of the conference because the loss and damage fund was created, but said that for further decarbonisation carbon pricing should be advanced and fossil fuel subsidies eliminated.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] Fossil fuel subsidies reached a record level of 7.1 trillion dollars in the year 2022, due to high fuel prices and inflation.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] There are propositions for a creation of a global carbon market managed by the United Nations in the conference.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] On 6 December 2023, Haitham al-Ghais, the current OPEC Secretary-General, urged member nations to focus negotiations on reducing carbon emissions, rather than prohibiting the extraction and sale of fossil fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] As a reaction, Greenpeace published a press release calling for Arab countries to phase out fossil fuels by 2050, ensuring a just transition.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2023-united-nations-climate-change-conference] If temperature rise will be limited to 1.5 degrees, the reduction in economic growth will be limited to 8.2% by 2050 and 36% by 2100.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] This article documents events, research findings, scientific and technological advances, and human actions to measure, predict, mitigate, and adapt to the effects of global warming and climate change—during the year 2024.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] paper to conclude that climate change's increase of water temperatures intensified peak wind speeds in all eleven 2024 Atlantic hurricanes.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] Scientists in the field of extreme event attribution have concluded that in virtually all countries and territories around the world in a year-long period beginning in May 2024, human-caused global warming has increased the number of days of extreme heat events over long-term norms.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] As a source of electric power in the EU, renewables overtook fossil fuels by 2020, and solar and wind together exceeded fossil fuels by 2025.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] The share of electricity coming from renewable sources continues to vary widely among European nations.
[src:efficient-energy-use/2024-in-climate-change] A few countries generate more electricity from renewables than is consumed in total.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] There are two main motivations to improve energy efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Firstly, one motivation is to achieve cost savings during the operation of the appliance or process.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] However, installing an energy-efficient technology comes with an upfront cost, the capital cost.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The different types of costs can be analyzed and compared with a life-cycle assessment.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Another motivation for energy efficiency is to reduce greenhouse gas emissions and hence work towards climate action.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] A focus on energy efficiency can also have a national security benefit because it can reduce the amount of energy that has to be imported from other countries.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency and renewable energy go hand in hand for sustainable energy policies.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] They are high priority actions in the energy hierarchy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy productivity, which measures the output and quality of goods and services per unit of energy input, can come from either reducing the amount of energy required to produce something, or from increasing the quantity or quality of goods and services from the same amount of energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] From the point of view of an energy consumer, the main motivation of energy efficiency is often simply saving money by lowering the cost of purchasing energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Additionally, from an energy policy point of view, there has been a long trend in a wider recognition of energy efficiency as the "first fuel", meaning the ability to replace or avoid the consumption of actual fuels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Moreover, it has long been recognized that energy efficiency brings other benefits additional to the reduction of energy consumption.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Some estimates of the value of these other benefits, often called *multiple benefits*, *co-benefits*, *ancillary benefits* or *non-energy benefits*, have put their summed value even higher than that of the direct energy benefits.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] These multiple benefits of energy efficiency include things such as reduced greenhouse gas emissions, reduced air pollution and improved health, and improved energy security.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Methods for calculating the monetary value of these multiple benefits have been developed, including e.g. the choice experiment method for improvements that have a subjective component (such as aesthetics or comfort) and Tuominen-Seppänen method for price risk reduction.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] When included in the analysis, the economic benefit of energy efficiency investments can be shown to be significantly higher than simply the value of the saved energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency has proved to be a cost-effective strategy for building economies without necessarily increasing energy consumption.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] For example, the state of California began implementing energy-efficiency measures in the mid-1970s, including building code and appliance standards with strict efficiency requirements.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] During the following years, California's energy consumption has remained approximately flat on a per capita basis while national US consumption doubled.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] As part of its strategy, California implemented a "loading order" for new energy resources that puts energy efficiency first, renewable electricity supplies second, and new fossil-fired power plants last.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] States such as Connecticut and New York have created quasi-public Green Banks to help residential and commercial building-owners finance energy efficiency upgrades that reduce emissions and cut consumers' energy costs.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy conservation is broader than energy efficiency in including active efforts to decrease energy consumption, for example through behaviour change, in addition to using energy more efficiently.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Examples of conservation without efficiency improvements are heating a room less in winter, using the car less, air-drying your clothes instead of using the dryer, or enabling energy saving modes on a computer.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] As with other definitions, the boundary between efficient energy use and energy conservation can be fuzzy, but both are important in environmental and economic terms.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency—using less energy to deliver the same goods or services, or delivering comparable services with less goods—is a cornerstone of many sustainable energy strategies.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The International Energy Agency (IEA) has estimated that increasing energy efficiency could achieve 40% of greenhouse gas emission reductions needed to fulfil the Paris Agreement's goals.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy can be conserved by increasing the technical efficiency of appliances, vehicles, industrial processes, and buildings.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] If the demand for energy services remains constant, improving energy efficiency will reduce energy consumption and carbon emissions.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] However, many efficiency improvements do not reduce energy consumption by the amount predicted by simple engineering models.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This is because they make energy services cheaper, and so consumption of those services increases.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] For example, since fuel efficient vehicles make travel cheaper, consumers may choose to drive farther, thereby offsetting some of the potential energy savings.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Similarly, an extensive historical analysis of technological efficiency improvements has conclusively shown that energy efficiency improvements were almost always outpaced by economic growth, resulting in a net increase in resource use and associated pollution.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] These are examples of the direct rebound effect.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Estimates of the size of the rebound effect range from roughly 5% to 40%.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The rebound effect is likely to be less than 30% at the household level and may be closer to 10% for transport.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] A rebound effect of 30% implies that improvements in energy efficiency should achieve 70% of the reduction in energy consumption projected using engineering models.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Modern appliances, such as, freezers, ovens, stoves, dishwashers, clothes washers and dryers, use significantly less energy than older appliances.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Current energy-efficient refrigerators, for example, use 40 percent less energy than conventional models did in 2001.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Following this, if all households in Europe changed their more than ten-year-old appliances into new ones, 20 billion kWh of electricity would be saved annually, hence reducing CO2 emissions by almost 18 billion kg.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In the US, the corresponding figures would be 17 billion kWh of electricity and 27,000,000,000 lb (1.2×1010 kg) CO2.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] According to a 2009 study from McKinsey & Company the replacement of old appliances is one of the most efficient global measures to reduce emissions of greenhouse gases.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Modern power management systems also reduce energy usage by idle appliances by turning them off or putting them into a low-energy mode after a certain time.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Many countries identify energy-efficient appliances using energy input labeling.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The impact of energy efficiency on peak demand depends on when the appliance is used.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] For example, an air conditioner uses more energy during the afternoon when it is hot.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Therefore, an energy-efficient air conditioner will have a larger impact on peak demand than off-peak demand.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] An energy-efficient dishwasher, on the other hand, uses more energy during the late evening when people do their dishes.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This appliance may have little to no impact on peak demand.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Over the period 2001–2021, tech companies have replaced traditional silicon switches in an electric circuit with quicker gallium nitride transistors to make new gadgets as energy efficient as feasible.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Gallium nitride transistors are, however, more costly.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This is a significant change in lowering the carbon footprint.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] A building's location and surroundings play a key role in regulating its temperature and illumination.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] For example, trees, landscaping, and hills can provide shade and block wind.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In cooler climates, designing northern hemisphere buildings with south facing windows and southern hemisphere buildings with north facing windows increases the amount of sun (ultimately heat energy) entering the building, minimizing energy use, by maximizing passive solar heating.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Tight building design, including energy-efficient windows, well-sealed doors, and additional thermal insulation of walls, basement slabs, and foundations can reduce heat loss by 25 to 50 percent.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Dark roofs may become up to 39 °C (70 °F) hotter than the most reflective white surfaces.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] They transmit some of this additional heat inside the building.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] US Studies have shown that lightly colored roofs use 40 percent less energy for cooling than buildings with darker roofs.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] White roof systems save more energy in sunnier climates.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Advanced electronic heating and cooling systems can moderate energy consumption and improve the comfort of people in the building.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Proper placement of windows and skylights as well as the use of architectural features that reflect light into a building can reduce the need for artificial lighting.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Increased use of natural and task lighting has been shown by one study to increase productivity in schools and offices.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Compact fluorescent lamps use two-thirds less energy and may last 6 to 10 times longer than incandescent light bulbs.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Newer fluorescent lights produce a natural light, and in most applications they are cost effective, despite their higher initial cost, with payback periods as low as a few months.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps use only about 10% of the energy an incandescent lamp requires.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design (LEED) is a rating system organized by the US Green Building Council (USGBC) to promote environmental responsibility in building design.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In 2013, USGBC developed the LEED Dynamic Plaque, a tool to track building performance against LEED metrics and a potential path to recertification.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The following year, the council collaborated with Honeywell to pull data on energy and water use, as well as indoor air quality from a BAS to automatically update the plaque, providing a near-real-time view of performance.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The USGBC office in Washington, D.C. is one of the first buildings to feature the live-updating LEED Dynamic Plaque.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Industries use a large amount of energy to power a diverse range of manufacturing and resource extraction processes.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Many industrial processes require large amounts of heat and mechanical power, most of which is delivered as natural gas, petroleum fuels, and electricity.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In addition some industries generate fuel from waste products that can be used to provide additional energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Because industrial processes are so diverse it is impossible to describe the multitude of possible opportunities for energy efficiency in industry.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Many depend on the specific technologies and processes in use at each industrial facility.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] There are, however, a number of processes and energy services that are widely used in many industries.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Various industries generate steam and electricity for subsequent use within their facilities.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] When electricity is generated, the heat that is produced as a by-product can be captured and used for process steam, heating or other industrial purposes.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Conventional electricity generation is about 30% efficient, whereas combined heat and power (also called co-generation) converts up to 90 percent of the fuel into usable energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Advanced boilers and furnaces can operate at higher temperatures while burning less fuel.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] These technologies are more efficient and produce fewer pollutants.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Over 45 percent of the fuel used by US manufacturers is burnt to make steam.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The typical industrial facility can reduce this energy usage 20 percent (according to the US Department of Energy) by insulating steam and condensate return lines, stopping steam leakage, and maintaining steam traps.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Electric motors usually run at a constant speed, but a variable speed drive allows the motor's energy output to match the required load.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This achieves energy savings ranging from 3 to 60 percent, depending on how the motor is used.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Motor coils made of superconducting materials can also reduce energy losses.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Motors may also benefit from voltage optimization.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Industry uses a large number of pumps and compressors of all shapes and sizes and in a wide variety of applications.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The efficiency of pumps and compressors depends on many factors but often improvements can be made by implementing better process control and better maintenance practices.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Compressors are commonly used to provide compressed air which is used for sand blasting, painting, and other power tools.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] According to the US Department of Energy, optimizing compressed air systems by installing variable speed drives, along with preventive maintenance to detect and fix air leaks, can improve energy efficiency 20 to 50 percent.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The estimated energy efficiency for an automobile is 280 Passenger-Mile/106 Btu.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to enhance a vehicle's energy efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Using improved aerodynamics to minimize drag can increase vehicle fuel efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Reducing vehicle weight can also improve fuel economy, which is why composite materials are widely used in car bodies.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] More advanced tires, with decreased tire to road friction and rolling resistance, can save gasoline.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Fuel economy can be improved by up to 3.3% by keeping tires inflated to the correct pressure.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Replacing a clogged air filter can improve a cars fuel consumption by as much as 10 percent on older vehicles.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] On newer vehicles (1980s and up) with fuel-injected, computer-controlled engines, a clogged air filter has no effect on mpg but replacing it may improve acceleration by 6-11 percent.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics also aid in efficiency of a vehicle.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The design of a car impacts the amount of gas needed to move it through air.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Aerodynamics involves the air around the car, which can affect the efficiency of the energy expended.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Turbochargers can increase fuel efficiency by allowing a smaller displacement engine.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The 'Engine of the year 2011' is the Fiat TwinAir engine equipped with an MHI turbocharger.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] "Compared with a 1.2-liter 8v engine, the new 85 HP turbo has 23% more power and a 30% better performance index.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy-efficient vehicles may reach twice the fuel efficiency of the average automobile.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Cutting-edge designs, such as the diesel Mercedes-Benz Bionic concept vehicle have achieved a fuel efficiency as high as 84 miles per US gallon (2.8 L/100 km; 101 mpg‑imp), four times the current conventional automotive average.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The mainstream trend in automotive efficiency is the rise of electric vehicles (all-electric or hybrid electric).
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Electric engines have more than double the efficiency of internal combustion engines.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Hybrids, like the Toyota Prius, use regenerative braking to recapture energy that would dissipate in normal cars; the effect is especially pronounced in city driving.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Plug-in hybrids also have increased battery capacity, which makes it possible to drive for limited distances without burning any gasoline; in this case, energy efficiency is dictated by whatever process (such as coal-burning, hydroelectric, or renewable source) created the power.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Plug-ins can typically drive for around 40 miles (64 km) purely on electricity without recharging; if the battery runs low, a gas engine kicks in allowing for extended range.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Finally, all-electric cars are also growing in popularity.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Cities around the globe light up millions of streets with 300 million lights.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Some cities are seeking to reduce street light power consumption by dimming lights during off-peak hours or switching to LED lamps.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] LED lamps are known to reduce the energy consumption by 50% to 80%.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] There are several ways to improve aviation's use of energy through modifications aircraft and air traffic management.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Aircraft improve with better aerodynamics, engines and weight.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Seat density and cargo load factors contribute to efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Air traffic management systems can allow automation of takeoff, landing, and collision avoidance, as well as within airports, from simple things like HVAC and lighting to more complex tasks such as security and scanning.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] At the 2023 United Nations Climate Change Conference, one of the adopted declaration was the GLOBAL RENEWABLES AND ENERGY EFFICIENCY PLEDGE signed by 123 countries.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The declaration includes obligations to consider energy efficiency as "first fuel" and double the rate of increase in energy efficiency from 2% per year to 4% per year by the year 2030.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] China and India did not sign this pledge.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] International standards ISO 17743 and ISO 17742 provide a documented methodology for calculating and reporting on energy savings and energy efficiency for countries and cities.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The first EU-wide energy efficiency target was set in 1998.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Member states agreed to improve energy efficiency by 1 percent a year over twelve years.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In addition, legislation about products, industry, transport and buildings has contributed to a general energy efficiency framework.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] More effort is needed to address heating and cooling: there is more heat wasted during electricity production in Europe than is required to heat all buildings in the continent.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] All in all, EU energy efficiency legislation is estimated to deliver savings worth the equivalent of up to 326 million tons of oil per year by 2020.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The EU set itself a 20% energy savings target by 2020 compared to 1990 levels, but member states decide individually how energy savings will be achieved.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] At an EU summit in October 2014, EU countries agreed on a new energy efficiency target of 27% or greater by 2030.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] One mechanism used to achieve the target of 27% is the 'Suppliers Obligations & White Certificates'.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The ongoing debate around the 2016 Clean Energy Package also puts an emphasis on energy efficiency, but the goal will probably remain around 30% greater efficiency compared to 1990 levels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Some have argued that this will not be enough for the EU to meet its Paris Agreement goals of reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 40% compared to 1990 levels.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In the European Union, 78% of enterprises proposed energy-saving methods in 2023, 67% listed energy contract renegotiation as a strategy, and 62% stated passing on costs to consumers as a plan to deal with energy market trends.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Larger organisations were found more likely to invest in energy efficiency, green innovation, and climate change, with a significant rise in energy efficiency investments reported by SMEs and mid-cap companies.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Energy efficiency is central to energy policy in Germany.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Progress toward improved efficiency has been steady.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Some however believe energy efficiency is still under-recognized in terms of its contribution to Germany's energy transformation (or *Energiewende*).
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Efforts to reduce final energy consumption in transport sector have not been successful, with a growth of 1.7% between 2005 and 2014.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This growth is due to both road passenger and road freight transport.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Both sectors increased their overall distance travelled to record the highest figures ever for Germany.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Rebound effects played a significant role, both between improved vehicle efficiency and the distance travelled, and between improved vehicle efficiency and an increase in vehicle weights and engine power.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In 2014, the German federal government released its National Action Plan on Energy Efficiency (NAPE).
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The areas covered are the energy efficiency of buildings, energy conservation for companies, consumer energy efficiency, and transport energy efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In 2016, the German government released a green paper on energy efficiency for public consultation (in German).
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] It outlines the potential challenges and actions needed to reduce energy consumption in Germany over the coming decades.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] At the document's launch, economics and energy minister Sigmar Gabriel said "we do not need to produce, store, transmit and pay for the energy that we save".
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The green paper prioritizes the efficient use of energy as the "first" response and also outlines opportunities for sector coupling, including using renewable power for heating and transport.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Other proposals include a flexible energy tax which rises as petrol prices fall, thereby incentivizing fuel conservation despite low oil prices.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In Spain, four out of every five buildings use more energy than they should.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] They are either inadequately insulated or consume energy inefficiently.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The Unión de Créditos Immobiliarios (UCI), which has operations in Spain and Portugal, is increasing loans to homeowners and building management groups for energy-efficiency initiatives.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] Their Residential Energy Rehabilitation initiative aims to remodel and encourage the use of renewable energy in at least 3720 homes in Madrid, Barcelona, Valencia, and Seville.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The works are expected to mobilize around €46.5 million in energy efficiency upgrades by 2025 and save approximately 8.1 GWh of energy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] It has the ability to reduce carbon emissions by 7,545 tonnes per year.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In May 2016 Poland adopted a new Act on Energy Efficiency, to enter into force on 1 October 2016.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In July 2009, the Council of Australian Governments, which represents the individual states and territories of Australia, agreed to a National Strategy on Energy Efficiency (NSEE).
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] This is a ten-year plan accelerating the implementation of a nationwide adoption of energy-efficient practices and a preparation for the country's transformation into a low carbon future.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The overriding agreement that governs this strategy is the National Partnership Agreement on Energy Efficiency.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] In August 2017, the Government of Canada released Build Smart - Canada's Buildings Strategy, as a key driver of the Pan-Canadian Framework on Clean Growth and Climate Change, Canada's national climate strategy.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] A 2011 Energy Modeling Forum study covering the United States examined how energy efficiency opportunities will shape future fuel and electricity demand over the next several decades.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] The US economy is already set to lower its energy and carbon intensity, but explicit policies will be necessary to meet climate goals.
[src:efficient-energy-use/efficient-energy-use] These policies include: a carbon tax, mandated standards for more efficient appliances, buildings and vehicles, and subsidies or reductions in the upfront costs of new more energy-efficient equipment.
